 the toes","Rotation of the tibia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe talonavicular joint is a synovial joint located in the foot, forming part of the transverse tarsal joint. It plays a crucial role in foot mobility and stability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe talonavicular joint primarily facilitates \u003Cstrong\u003Einversion and eversion of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E. This joint, along with the calcaneocuboid joint, forms the transverse tarsal joint, which allows the foot to adapt to uneven surfaces by enabling these movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexion and extension of the toes\u003C/strong\u003E - These movements occur at the metatarsophalangeal and interphalangeal joints\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsiflexion and plantarflexion of the ankle\u003C/strong\u003E - These movements occur at the ankle joint\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbduction and adduction of the toes\u003C/strong\u003E - These movements occur at the metatarsophalangeal joints\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotation of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E - This movement is not facilitated by the talonavicular joint\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The talonavicular joint is a part of the transverse tarsal joint, which allows for complex foot movements.","The talonavicular joint primarily allows for inversion and eversion of the foot.","The joint also contributes to the foot\u0027s ability to adapt to uneven surfaces."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemic